  "reasoning": "I can see some current TSA data. Let me fetch the actual TSA passenger volumes page and historical data to build a proper forecast.I need the 2025 historical data for the comparable week. Let me fetch the 2025 archive and also get 2024 data.Now let me compute the weekly totals and analyze patterns.Now let me write my meta-reflection and provide the final forecast.## Forecast Summary: TSA Passenger Volume (Feb 23 - Mar 1, 2026)\n\n**Median estimate: ~16.8M passengers**\n\n### Key Evidence\n- **2025 base**: The directly comparable week (Feb 24 - Mar 2, 2025) saw **16,410,407** passengers\n- **2024 base**: The comparable week (Feb 26 - Mar 3, 2024) saw **16,334,405** passengers\n- **2026 YoY growth**: Early February 2026 data shows **+2.4% to +4.4%** growth vs 2025\n- **Industry outlook**: BCG projects 5.8% global air travel growth in 2026; record 3M-passenger day hit in January\n\n### Methodology\nThree independent estimation methods converge:\n1. **Monte Carlo simulation** (100k runs, 2.5% ± 1.2% growth, 1.5% weekly noise): median **16.81M**\n2. **Presidents Day ratio method**: **16.94M**\n3. **Early-Feb ratio method**: **16.56M**\n\n### Distribution (Percentiles)\n| P10 | P20 | P40 | P60 | P80 | P90 |\n|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|\n| 16.36M | 16.52M | 16.72M | 16.89M | 17.08M | 17.23M |\n\nThe distribution is moderately tight because this is a well-patterned metric with strong seasonal regularity. A ~3% disruption tail risk from potential winter storms provides the left-tail extension.",
